\pard\f0\fs36\qc BALANOPHORALES
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 46.         BALANOPHORACEAE}
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  Edit. D.A. Webb
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Herbs without chlorophyll, parasitic on the roots of other plants. Flowers usually unisexual, in dense, spicate or capitate inflorescences. Fruit a small, 1-seeded nut; seed with abundant endosperm and minute embryo.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 1.             Cynomorium}              L.
\par    

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By D.A. Webb.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial. Male, female and hermaphrodite flowers present. Perianth of 1-5 linear to cuneate or oblanceolate segments, partly fused to the ovary in female and hermaphrodite flowers. Stamen 1, epigynous. Style and stigma 1.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Literature: J. Léonard,{\i  Bull. Jard. Bot. Nat. Belg. }{\b 56:} 301-304 (1986).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. C. coccineum} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 970 (1753). Plant dark red to purplish-black. Stems 15-30 cm, arising from a branched, underground rhizome, erect, stout, fleshy, bearing numerous triangular-lanceolate scale-leaves. Inflorescence 6-12 × 2-4 cm, terminal, cylindrical-clavate, with a stout, fleshy axis on which are numerous dense, subcapitate cymes subtended by triangular-peltate, deciduous bracts.{\i  Parasitic on various plants, usually in saline habitats. Mediterranean region, mainly in the west; S. Portugal; very local}. Bl Co Hs It Lu Sa Si.
